    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA24-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu poruḷ pirivukku uṭaṉpaṭṭa toḻiyait talaivi uvantu kūṟiyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">What SHE said joyfully to the confidante who agreed to the separation [for the sake] of wealth.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA24">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            pārpaka vīḻnta vēruṭai viḻukkōṭ</l>
<l>            ṭuṭumpaṭain taṉṉa neṭumpori viḷavi</l>
<l>            ṉāṭṭoḻi pantiṟ kōṭṭumūk kiṟupu</l>
<l>            kampalat taṉṉa paimpayirt tāam</l>
<l>            veḷḷil valci vēṟṟunāṭ ṭāriṭaic </l>
<l>            cēṟu nāmeṉac collac cēyiḻai</l>
<l>            naṉṟeṉap purintōy naṉṟucey taṉaiyē</l>
<l>            ceyalpaṭu maṉattar ceyporuṭ</l>
<l>            kakalva rāṭava ratuvataṉ paṇpē.</l>
        </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>"We shall go</l>
<l rend="indent">a difficult way to a different land, with wood-apple for food,</l>
<l rend="indent2">that spread [as] fresh crops like a blanket,</l>
<l rend="indent3">after the noses<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">mūkku</term> apparently refers to the fruits of the wood-apple. Why "noses"? Does this mean a peculiar form or is it just what protrudes from the branches?</note> on the branches perished,</l>
<l rend="indent4">like balls staying behind after play,</l>
<l rend="indent3">of the long, parched wood-apple tree, set(?) like Uṭumpu trees</l>
<l rend="indent4">with excellent branches possessing roots that come down so as to split the rock",</l>
<l rend="indent4">when [he] said so, o you of red jewels,</l>
<l>you who wished [him] well, have done a good thing.</l>
<l>Men are such as depart for wealth to be made,</l>
<l>[their] minds set on action. That’s its<note place="foot">To what does the <term xml:lang="ta">ataṉ</term>, n.sg. obl., refer here? The nature of life itself?</note> nature.</l>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="1+2b">
    <l>of the long, parched wood-apple tree, like seated lizards,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">uṭumpu</term> is a problematic word. In most other places (including several in PN: 68.1, 152.5, etc.) is seems to refer to a kind of lizard (thus the entry in the TL), be it with some fabulous traits, but here T.V.G. suggests to take it as a kind of tree, probably because <term xml:lang="ta">kōṭṭu</term>, "branch", occurs twice (in lines 1 and 3), so that in the case of the lizard solution the <term xml:lang="ta">uṭumpu</term> would appear to be endowed with roots and branches. This problem, however, can be circumvented by reading <term xml:lang="ta">uṭump’ aṭaintaṉṉa</term> as a brief, inserted second simile given for the fruits of the wood-apple tree. The result is not very satisfactory either way: either we have a wood-apple tree compared to an otherwise unknown <term xml:lang="ta">uṭumpu</term> tree, or we have to put up with two similes for the wood-apple tree’s fruit and a double mentioning of its branches.</note></l>
    <l>excellent branches possessing descending roots</l>
    <l>so that the rock is split”,</l>
</lg>
        
        </lg>
         </div>
